  "prompt": "Is Sri Ramakrishna Paramahamsa an avatar?",
  "response": "Sri Ramakrishna Paramahamsa (1836\u20131886) is highly revered as a saint, mystic, and spiritual teacher in Hinduism. Whether he is considered an *avatar* (a divine incarnation) depends largely on individual beliefs and interpretations within different spiritual and religious communities.\n\n### Understanding \"Avatar\"\n\nIn Hindu theology, an *avatar* typically refers to the descent of a deity, most commonly associated with Lord Vishnu, to Earth in various forms to restore dharma (cosmic order) and guide humanity. Traditional avatars include well-known figures like Rama, Krishna, and Buddha (in some traditions).\n\n### Sri Ramakrishna's Status\n\nSri Ramakrishna is celebrated for his profound spiritual experiences, teachings on universalism, and efforts to harmonize different religious paths. While mainstream Hinduism does not traditionally classify him as an *avatar* in the same sense as deities like Vishnu or Shiva, his followers and the Ramakrishna Order often regard him as a divinely inspired figure whose life and teachings provide a living example of spiritual realization.\n\n### Varied Perspectives\n\n1. **Devotees and Followers**: Many of Sri Ramakrishna\u2019s devotees view him as an embodiment of divine consciousness, sometimes referring to him as an *avatar* or divine incarnation. They believe that his life was a manifestation of the divine purpose to guide humanity towards spiritual enlightenment.\n\n2. **Traditional Hindu Scholarship**: From a more orthodox standpoint, *avatars* are specific divine manifestations with particular roles in maintaining cosmic balance. In this view, while Sri Ramakrishna is deeply respected and considered a great saint, he may not be categorized as an *avatar* in the traditional theological sense.\n\n3. **Interfaith and Modern Interpretations**: In contemporary spiritual discourse, the boundaries of terms like *avatar* can be more fluid. Some modern interpretations embrace a broader understanding of divine manifestations, which may include revered spiritual leaders like Sri Ramakrishna.\n\n### Conclusion\n\nWhether Sri Ramakrishna Paramahamsa is regarded as an *avatar* depends on one's spiritual beliefs, religious affiliations, and interpretations of his life and teachings. He is universally acknowledged as a profound and influential spiritual figure whose impact extends beyond specific religious classifications.",
